05444nam a22008655i 9783110691788DE-B159720230228015514.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230228t20202020gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831106917887 a10.1515/97831106917882doi  a(DE-B1597)544688  a(OCoLC)1191863886  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aREL0061002bisacsh1 aWoodington, J. David, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Dubious Disciples :bDoubt and Disbelief in the Post-Resurrection Scenes of the Four Gospels /cJ. David Woodington. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (VII, 224 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aBeihefte zur Zeitschrift für die neutestamentliche Wissenschaft ,x0171-6441 ;v24100tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- t1 Introduction -- t2 The Gospel Of Mark -- t3 The Gospel Of Matthew -- t4 The Gospel Of Luke -- t5 The Gospel Of John -- tConclusion -- tAppendix: The Disciples In Ancient Christianity -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Dubious Disciples provides a literary examination of the four scenes of the disciples doubting the appearance of the resurrected Jesus in the canonical Gospels. Each Gospel offers a unique account of this episode, and the differences between them dramatically affect how readers evaluate the disciples' actions and perceive the role of doubt in the Christian experience.  aThe accounts of Jesus's resurrection in the Gospels are among the most widely discussed passages in the New Testament, and a classic element of the resurrection story is the doubt felt by the disciples when they encountered the risen Lord. In spite of this, scholars have paid relatively little attention to the striking divergences in the portrayal of the disciples across the four Gospels. The Longer Ending of Mark has them stubbornly refuse to believe multiple reports of the resurrection before being upbraided by Christ, Matthew tersely notes their doubts in a single verse and never resolves the problem, Luke depicts a group who are simultaneously terrified and joyful, and John describes the eponymous Doubting Thomas and his request to touch the risen Lord for himself. The Dubious Disciples uses narrative criticism to examine the ways in which each Gospel characterizes the disciples post-resurrection and how these authorial choices influence readers' evaluations of both the disciples' doubts and the doubts they may feel in their own lives. The lessons learned about the nature of doubt vary considerably from one Gospel to the next, and this monograph is the first devoted to a comparison of doubt across all four Gospels.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aApostles. 0aBelief and doubt. 7aRELIGION / Biblical Criticism & Interpretation / New Testament.2bisacsh  aGospels.  aResurrection.  adiscipleship.  adoubt.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Ebook Package English 2020z978311069628808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus DeG Package 2020 Part 1z978311069627108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Theol., Relig.Stud., Jewish Stud. 2020 Englishz978311070477808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Theol., Relig.Stud., Jewish Stud. 2020z9783110704570oZDB-23-DGF0 cEPUBz97831106918250 cprintz978311069155940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311069178840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110691788423Coveruhttps://www.degruyt